// BT-2746 / ADR 0102 §3/§4: `\` difference and `&` intersection type
// annotations, plus advisory `match:` exhaustiveness for singleton unions.
//
// Pins, across the parser/semantic snapshots:
//   - a valid `\` difference annotation (BT-2742);
//   - a valid `&` intersection annotation (BT-2743);
//   - a non-exhaustive `match:` over a closed singleton union — an advisory
//     Warning, never an Error (ADR 0102 §4). This is the ONE place the
//     warning-*appearing* case is pinned end-to-end through the compiler
//     pipeline, per BT-2745's finding that BUnit cannot observe warnings.
//   - the `\\`-typo targeted parse error (did-you-mean `\`);
//   - the deliberate parse error for mixing `&`/`\` without parentheses.
//
// The two error cases below are recoverable parse errors — the parser
// continues past them (error-node recovery), so the remaining, well-formed
// class still parses, type-checks and codegens; only the parser snapshot
// records the diagnostics.

Object subclass: SetTheoreticOperatorsCase

  // Valid `\` difference annotation (BT-2742/ADR 0102 §3): "any Symbol
  // except #foo".
  tagWithoutFoo -> Symbol \ #foo => #bar

  // Valid `&` intersection annotation (BT-2743/ADR 0102 §3): class ∩
  // protocol — the irreducible case, ADR 0102 §1.
  describe: value :: Integer & Printable -> String => value asString

  // Non-exhaustive `match:` over a closed singleton-union scrutinee — `#west`
  // is not handled and there is no wildcard arm, so the type checker emits
  // an advisory Warning (never an Error) naming the residual (ADR 0102 §4).
  classify: heading :: #north | #south | #east | #west -> String =>
    heading match: [
      #north -> "up";
      #south -> "down";
      #east -> "right"
    ]

// The two error cases below are standalone (Tonel-style `Class >> method`)
// extension methods rather than new `subclass:` definitions, so they do not
// trip the unrelated one-class-per-file check (BT-1666) — only the class
// above counts toward `module.classes`.

// The lexer greedily merges `\\` into the modulo selector; in type position
// this is almost certainly a typo for the difference operator `\`, so it gets
// a targeted "did you mean `\`" diagnostic rather than a generic parse error.
Object >> bt2746DoubleBackslashTypo -> Symbol \\ #foo => #bar

// Mixing `&` and `\` in one type-annotation chain without explicit grouping
// is a deliberate parse error (ADR 0102 §3) — `(Printable & Comparable) \
// #foo` and `Printable & (Comparable \ #foo)` differ and neither reading is
// obviously dominant. Grouping parentheses do not exist in type-annotation
// position today, so there is currently no way to write either reading
// explicitly; this is a documented limitation, not an oversight in this test.
//
// Recovery keeps building using the first-committed operator (`&`), so the
// annotation still resolves — to `Intersection{Printable, Comparable} & #foo`,
// which normalises to `Never` (a protocol intersection has no member in
// common with an unrelated singleton). That produces a *second*, knock-on
// semantic warning ("declares return type Never, but body returns Object") —
// an honest consequence of parse-error recovery, not a second bug to fix.
Object >> bt2746MixedOperators -> Printable & Comparable \ #foo => self
